sprysound

Class Playback

  • java.lang.Object
    • sprysound.Playback
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    PreloadedPlayback, StreamingPlayback

    public abstract class Playback
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a single instance of playback, which occurs when audio data is actively being played. A Playback object is created and returned to the caller every time one of the play methods of an Audio object is called. A Playback object is initialized with the attributes (volume, number of loops to be played) that were (optionally) passed as arguments to a play method, and the Playback object will thus represent an instance of playback with those attributes. A Playback will run in its own thread and can be controlled (paused, resumed, stopped, etc.) and have its mutable attributes (e.g. volume) modified through its interface, independent of the Audio object that created it.

    There is a many-to-one relationship between Playback object(s) and the Audio object that spawned them.

    Author:
    Christian Holton
